                      FEMMA C++ — Licensing
                      =====================

This directory contains two parts under two licences:

  (1) Core library and everything outside src/mma/  ......  MIT
  (2) Optimiser in src/mma/  .............................  GPL-3.0-or-later

Every source file carries an SPDX-License-Identifier line stating its licence.


------------------------------------------------------------------------
Why two licences, and what the COMBINED build is
------------------------------------------------------------------------

The files in src/mma/ (subsolv, mmasub, kktcheck, asymp, gcmmasub, concheck,
raaupdate) are a C++ translation of Krister Svanberg's MMA / GCMMA reference
code, which is distributed under the GNU General Public License for academic,
non-commercial use.  These files are therefore GPL-3.0-or-later.

Every other file is an original translation of the FEMMA MATLAB code and is
offered under the MIT licence (reproduced below).

When the core is compiled and linked together with src/mma/ into a single
library or executable, the result is a combined work that includes GPL code.
Such a combined work, when distributed, is governed AS A WHOLE by the
GPL-3.0-or-later.  In plain terms: the binary you build and ship is GPL, even
though most of the individual source files are MIT.


------------------------------------------------------------------------
Relicensing the core
------------------------------------------------------------------------

Because the MIT-licensed core does not derive from Svanberg's work, a fully
permissive build is possible: replace src/mma/ with an independent CCSA / MMA
optimiser (for example NLopt's CCSA) behind the interface declared in
include/femma/mma.hpp.  Nothing in src/core/ depends on the Svanberg sources
beyond that header, so the rest of the library can then be used under the MIT
licence alone.


------------------------------------------------------------------------
Full licence texts
------------------------------------------------------------------------

The full text of the GNU General Public License version 3 is available at
<https://www.gnu.org/licenses/gpl-3.0.txt>.  Place a copy named COPYING beside
this file before redistributing.  See THIRD_PARTY_NOTICES.md for citations of
Svanberg's work.

The MIT licence text governing part (1) follows, then the GPL notice for
part (2).


